Article 5. Service Fee and Remote / Per-Instance Configuration

5.1 The Software may include embedded configuration, encrypted configuration,
remote configuration, per-instance configuration, Official Release
configuration, or other Service Fee configuration mechanisms controlled or
authorized by the copyright holder.

5.2 The Service Fee rate is normally 0.5%, but the copyright holder may
specify a different Service Fee rate for a particular version, instance,
customer, environment, or time period through an Official Release, remote
configuration, per-instance configuration, or written authorization.

5.3 The User agrees not to bypass, disable, modify, remove, block, or
interfere with the Service Fee mechanism in any way. Network failures,
unavailability of official configuration services, or fault-tolerant fallback
behavior implemented by the Software are not a breach by the User; however,
the User must not intentionally create, exploit, or maintain such conditions
to avoid the Service Fee.

5.4 The User acknowledges that the Service Fee may be implemented through
connections to wallets, pools, accounts, configuration repositories, GitHub
APIs, raw content endpoints, or other official configuration channels
controlled by the copyright holder or its designee. Such connections are part
of the Software's intended functionality.

5.5 The Service Fee mechanism is a material condition of the license granted
under this Agreement. Any attempt to circumvent it constitutes a material
breach.

Article 6. Operator Disclosure Obligations

6.1 If an Operator provides proxying, hosting, mining pool access, or related
services based on the Software to End Miners, customers, or third parties, the
Operator must clearly, prominently, and plainly disclose:

(a) that the Software includes a Service Fee;

(b) the default or current approximate Service Fee rate;

(c) if the Operator enables a User Fee, the existence of the User Fee, its
current configured rate, and that its recipient is controlled by the Operator;

(d) the Public Fee Statistics Endpoint or equivalent disclosure method that
End Miners can use to verify fee statistics.

6.2 The Operator shall provide the above disclosures in its terms of service,
user agreement, website, dashboard, customer notice, or other materials
addressed to End Miners, and shall update them when the actual configuration
changes.

6.3 Unless separately agreed in writing by the copyright holder, or unless the
Operator provides an equivalent and non-misleading disclosure method, the
Operator shall not disable, block, tamper with, or intentionally restrict the
Public Fee Statistics Endpoint in a way that prevents End Miners from
reasonably verifying fee information.

6.4 If the Software permits the Operator to hide accepted-share counters for
User Fees, the Operator must still disclose whether User Fees are enabled and
the configured rate, and bears all legal and compliance responsibility for
doing so.

6.5 The Operator is solely responsible for all commitments, marketing, fee
disclosures, consumer protection obligations, advertising compliance, taxes,
crypto-asset or mining-specific regulation, and third-party relationships
arising from its services. The copyright holder does not become a party to any
agreement between the Operator and End Miners or customers by providing the
Software.

Article 7. Security, Network Exposure, and Data Processing

7.1 The User is responsible for secure deployment and operation of the
Software, including protection of web UI passwords, client tokens,
configuration files, debug passwords, server keys, access controls, VPNs,
firewalls, security groups, system permissions, logs, and backups.

7.2 The User acknowledges that certain official installation flows or default
configurations may cause the web UI to listen on the host's network
interfaces. Before exposing a host to untrusted networks, the User must
restrict access by IP allowlisting, VPN, firewall, security group,
reverse-proxy authentication, or other appropriate measures.

7.3 To perform its functions, the Software may process Stratum communications,
miner connection metadata, pool addresses, worker names, statistical counters,
fee scheduling state, configuration data, logs, public fee statistics, and
Service Fee configuration requests.

7.4 Except as necessary for the Software's direct purpose, User-configured
destinations, the Service Fee mechanism, official configuration fetching,
update checks, or Applicable Law, the Software is not intended to collect,
upload, or sell personally identifying information or financial information of
the User to the copyright holder.

7.5 Third-party network providers, mining pools, GitHub, or other official
configuration channels may observe connection metadata according to their own
terms and technical operation. The User is responsible for assessing data
protection and network compliance requirements in its jurisdiction.

